Quick proof (run this)
SELECT
  COUNT(*) AS rows_in_er30,
  COUNT(DISTINCT GMPI_ID) AS distinct_gmpi
FROM #er30;

SELECT
  COUNT(*) AS rows_in_dim_member_for_er30,
  COUNT(DISTINCT dm.GMPI_ID) AS distinct_gmpi_in_dim
FROM BI_ANALYSIS.dbo.dim_member dm
JOIN #er30 e ON e.GMPI_ID = dm.GMPI_ID;

If rows_in_dim_member_for_er30 > distinct_gmpi_in_dim, then dim_member has duplicates per GMPI.

✅ Fix: Join to only ONE row per GMPI_ID from dim_member

Pick the “best” member row using ROW_NUMBER() (prefer ACTIVE_FLAG=1, else latest DW_UPDATE_DATE).

Replace your final SELECT with this version (copy/paste whole Step 2+3):

/* STEP 2 + 3: Final Output (dedupe dim_member + aggregate procedures) */

SELECT
    dm1.GMPI_ID,
    dm1.MEMBER_MBI,
    dm1.MEMBER_FIRST_NAME,
    dm1.MEMBER_LAST_NAME,
    dm1.MEMBER_DATE_OF_BIRTH,

    e.LAST_ER_DATE,
    e.CLAIM_ID_ER,
    e.HOSPITAL_PROVIDER,
    e.ER_STATUS,
    e.ER_CATEGORY,

    p.PROC_LINE_COUNT,
    p.ALL_PROCEDURE_CODES

FROM #er30 e

LEFT JOIN (
    SELECT *
    FROM (
        SELECT
            dm.*,
            ROW_NUMBER() OVER (
                PARTITION BY dm.GMPI_ID
                ORDER BY
                    CASE WHEN dm.ACTIVE_FLAG = 1 THEN 1 ELSE 2 END,
                    dm.DW_UPDATE_DATE DESC
            ) AS rn
        FROM BI_ANALYSIS.dbo.dim_member dm
    ) x
    WHERE x.rn = 1
) dm1
    ON dm1.GMPI_ID = e.GMPI_ID

LEFT JOIN (
    SELECT
        fcp.CLAIM_ID,
        COUNT(*) AS PROC_LINE_COUNT,
        STRING_AGG(CAST(fcp.CODE AS VARCHAR(MAX)), ',') AS ALL_PROCEDURE_CODES
    FROM BI_ANALYSIS.dbo.FACT_CLAIM_PROCEDURE fcp
    JOIN #er30 e2
        ON e2.CLAIM_ID_ER = fcp.CLAIM_ID
    GROUP BY fcp.CLAIM_ID
) p
    ON p.CLAIM_ID = e.CLAIM_ID_ER

ORDER BY e.LAST_ER_DATE DESC;
Why this removes duplicates

The subquery dm1 forces exactly 1 row per GMPI_ID from dim_member.

So each #er30 row can match only one member row → no multiplication.

